            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-field-body field--type-text-long field--label-hidden field__item"><h3>Introduction to woodcarving: comfort birds</h3>
<p>Friday, July 18 from 1 pm to 5 pm<br>
Ages 16 and up<br>
Cost:&nbsp;$85 + tax (per person)<br>
<a href="https://anc.ca.apm.activecommunities.com/ottawa/activity/search/detail/148951?onlineSiteId=0&amp;locale=en-US&amp;from_original_cui=true">Advance registration is required.</a></p>
<p>Led by Martin Thornell from Ottawa City Woodshop, participants will learn and apply basic whittling and carving skills to create their own “comfort bird.” Comfort birds are small carvings that fit in the palm of the hand. This workshop is the perfect opportunity to pick up a new hobby while enjoying beautiful views of the Ottawa River! All skill levels, including beginners, are welcome. All supplies are included in the cost of registration; light refreshments will be served.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Notes:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The primary language of delivery for this program is English.</li>
<li>There are two accessible parking spaces located in the parking lot closest to the museum. The workshop will take place outside on a grass lawn and under sun cover, or inside the museum on the main floor. There is an accessible bathroom located via gravel path. Additional&nbsp;<a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/node/1007490/">information about accessibility</a>&nbsp;can be found on the museum web page. If you have questions or concerns regarding accessibility, please contact the museum by phone at 613-832-4347 or by email at&nbsp;<a href="mailto:museums@ottawa.ca">museums@ottawa.ca</a>.</li>
<li>Advance registration is required. Workshops with insufficient registration may be cancelled. If an alternative cannot be offered, a refund will be issued.</li>
<li>Visit the&nbsp;<a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/family-and-social-services/older-adults/financial-assistance#section-89551f56-14c3-4f6e-b24c-5e5072350977">Ottawa Hand in Hand</a>&nbsp;web page for information on available financial supports to facilitate participation in recreation and culture programs.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Medicine shield workshop</h3>
<p>Friday, August 15 from 1 pm to 2:30 pm<br>
Ages 16 and up.<br>
Cost: $75 + tax (per person) .&nbsp;<a href="https://anc.ca.apm.activecommunities.com/ottawa/activity/search/detail/149104?onlineSiteId=0&amp;locale=en-US&amp;from_original_cui=true"><strong>Advance registration is required.</strong></a></p>
<p>Led by&nbsp;<a href="https://www.makatew.ca/" target="_blank">Makatew Workshops</a>, visitors are invited to learn the significance and use of medicine shields while making their own. Participants will also discuss topics like truth and reconciliation, providing an open environment to ask questions without judgment. All skill levels, including beginners, are welcome. This workshop will take place outdoors; an indoor space will be provided in the event of inclement weather. Materials and supplies are provided. Light refreshments will be served.</p>
<p><strong>Meet the workshop facilitator:&nbsp;</strong>Marc Forgette is an Indigenous entrepreneur, educator, and speaker dedicated to fostering cultural awareness and reconciliation. As the founder of Makatew Workshops, Marc delivers hands-on experiences that provide meaningful learning opportunities for corporate, government, and institutional audiences. His expertise in Indigenous traditions, combined with his engaging approach, has earned him multiple awards, including the Think Ottawa 2024 Market Leadership Award, MPI Ottawa's Supplier of the Year, and the 2024 Influence Award. In 2025, Marc is expanding his impact with the launch of Makatew Speaks, a new division of Makatew dedicated to keynote speaking and thought leadership. Through this initiative, he will share insights on Indigenous business challenges, cultural appreciation, and the importance of Indigenous-led initiatives at conferences, corporate events, and educational institutions. With a passion for creating safe and inclusive spaces for learning, Marc is committed to building bridges between Indigenous and non-Indigenous communities through education, storytelling, and collaboration</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Notes:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The primary language of delivery for this program is English.</li>
<li>There are two accessible parking spaces located in the parking lot closest to the museum. The workshop will take place outside on a grass lawn and under sun cover, or inside the museum on the main floor. There is an accessible bathroom located via gravel path. Additional&nbsp;<a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/node/1007490/">information about accessibility</a>&nbsp;can be found on the museum web page. If you have questions or concerns regarding accessibility, please contact the museum by phone at 613-832-4347 or by email at&nbsp;<a href="mailto:museums@ottawa.ca">museums@ottawa.ca</a>.</li>
<li>Advance registration is required. Workshops with insufficient registration may be cancelled. If an alternative cannot be offered, a refund will be issued.</li>
<li>Visit the&nbsp;<a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/family-and-social-services/older-adults/financial-assistance#section-89551f56-14c3-4f6e-b24c-5e5072350977">Ottawa Hand in Hand</a>&nbsp;web page for information on available financial supports to facilitate participation in recreation and culture programs.</li>
</ul>
