            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-field-body field--type-text-long field--label-hidden field__item"><h3>Pinhey's Past-Times</h3>
<p>June 29, July 5 and July 6 from 10 am to 4 pm<br>
Cost: Pay-What-You-Can</p>
<p>Complement your visit to Pinhey’s Point Historic Site with a heritage demonstration or hands-on activity. Explore a trade, pastime, or recipe inspired by the experiences of Hamnett K. Pinhey (1784-1857), his family, or those who live alongside and make use of the Ottawa River.</p>
<p>*Please note that the schedule of demonstrations and activities is subject to change. This program is delivered in English, however, all reasonable efforts will be made to have a bilingual (English/French) staff member available to assist.</p>
<p><strong>June 29 - Outaouais Woodcarvers</strong></p>
<p>Join members of the <a href="https://www.owcarvers.com/events">Outaouais Woodcarvers </a>to learn more about woodcarving! You will get to smooth and polish a fiddlestick, and staff will be on hand with some more hands-on activities for you to enjoy. Please note that supplies are limited</p>
<p><strong>July 5 - Ottawa Guild of Lacemakers</strong></p>
<p>Members of the Ottawa Guild of Lacemakers will be on-site to teach you more about lacemaking! Join museum staff to try your hand at some of the lacemaking techniques that the guild will be demonstrating.</p>
<p><strong>July 6 - Makatew Workshops</strong></p>
<p>Nestled along the Ottawa River, this land was&nbsp;likely a stop for many different Indigenous&nbsp;groups, including the Anishinabe Algonquin&nbsp;peoples, long before it became home to&nbsp;generations of the Pinhey family. Led by <a href="https://www.makatew.ca/">Makatew Workshops</a>, visitors are invited to learn the significance and use of medicine bags while making their own using locally sourced deer leather. Please note that supplies are limited.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
